        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What foods should be on a high-protein grocery list for men over 40?</h3>
          <p>The most efficient choices are chicken breast, canned tuna, canned salmon, 93% lean ground beef, Greek yogurt, cottage cheese, eggs, shrimp, rotisserie chicken, and whey protein as a backup. These deliver 20–50g of protein per serving with minimal preparation.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>How many high-protein foods do you need to hit 120g per day?</h3>
          <p>Most men over 40 can cover 120g using 4–6 foods they rotate weekly. The 80/20 rule applies: a handful of high-density protein foods cover the majority of your daily target. You don't need a 50-item grocery list — you need the right 10–15 foods stocked consistently.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is the cheapest high-protein food for men over 40?</h3>
          <p>Canned tuna and eggs are the best value. A 5-oz can of tuna delivers 25g of protein for under $2. Two eggs give you 12g for about $0.50. Chicken breast bought in bulk is also very cost-effective at roughly $0.50–$0.75 per 10g of protein.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Do men over 40 need protein powder to hit their protein goals?</h3>
          <p>No — whole foods can cover the full 120g daily target without protein powder. Powder is a convenient backup for days when meals fall short, not a requirement. If your grocery list is stocked with the right foods, powder is optional.</p>
